    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - SINGLE SPEED AXLE: SPICER - DISASSEMBLE - PINION</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="9">
        <title>PINION</title>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1400720">Figure 20</hotlnk>.
        </para>
        <figure id="f1400720" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1400720" filename="../figg14/G1400720.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 20. Pinion Exploded View</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove pinion cage mounting bolts (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400721">Figure 21</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400721" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400721" filename="../figg14/G1400721.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 21. Remove Pinion Cage Mounting Bolts</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove pinion and cage assembly from carrier housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400722">Figure 22</hotlnk>). If difficulty is encountered in removing pinion assembly
                from carrier housing, place brass drift on inner end of pinion gear and tap lightly.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400722" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400722" filename="../figg14/G1400722.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 22. Remove Pinion and Cage Assembly From Carrier Housing</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Retain shims for possible use during reassembly.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para></para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Holding yoke stationary, remove nut and washer. Use of a torque multiplier may be necessary
                (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400723">Figure 23</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400723" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400723" filename="../figg14/G1400723.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 23. Remove Nut and Washer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the end yoke using a suitable puller (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400724">Figure 24</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400724" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400724" filename="../figg14/G1400724.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 24. Remove End Yoke</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove pinion gear from cage assembly.</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It may be necessary to tap outer end of pinion gear with a soft hammer. Replace pinion nut,
                        flush with end of pinion, so damage to threads does not occur.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Located between pinion bearings is a selective spacer, used for pinion bearing preload.
                Retain this spacer for possible use in reassembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400725">Figure 25</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400725" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400725" filename="../figg14/G1400725.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 25. Selective Spacer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove old pinion seal and discard. Always replace it with a new seal at time of
                reassembly.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Lift out outer pinion bearing cone.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove inner pinion bearing cup, using a suitable adapter and press or puller (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400726">Figure 26</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400726" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400726" filename="../figg14/G1400726.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 26. Remove Inner Pinion Bearing Cup</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not nick bearing bore.</para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove outer pinion bearing cup, using same procedure as Step 9.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove pinion roller bearing from end of pinion (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400727">Figure 27</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400727" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400727" filename="../figg14/G1400727.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 27. Remove Pinion Roller Bearing</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove inner bearing cone from pinion gear (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400728">Figure 28</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400728" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400728" filename="../figg14/G1400728.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 28. Remove Inner Bearing Cone</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
